article.headline: Indiana 62, Charlotte 53
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Tamika Catchings says she knew the Indiana
Fever needed to dominate on the boards against the Charlotte Sting.

She did her best to help, grabbing a career-high 16 rebounds --
10 offensive -- and scoring 18 points to lead the Fever to a 62-53
victory over Charlotte on Saturday night. Indiana had a 39-22
rebounding advantage.

It was Catchings' ninth double-double of the season and the 37th
of her career as a season-high crowd of 9,823 saw Indiana score 28
points off 21 Charlotte turnovers, while the Sting scored only 12
points following 19 Indiana turnovers.

"We knew we had to go on the boards. We've been slipping a
little bit the last couple of games," said Catchings, who fell one
rebound short of tying the franchise mark for a single game. "One
of the things we talked about is we got to get on the boards ...
try to create more looks."

Natalie Williams added 11 points and 10 rebounds for Indiana,
bringing her career total of double-doubles to 68. Kelly Miller
added 13 points for Indiana.

Charlotte trailed for most of the game but managed to pull
within six points late with Sheri Sam scoring nine of her team-high
15 points in the second half.

"They were playing hard. They have some talent on that team.
They haven't given up," Indiana coach Brian Winters said. "They
were very aggressive defensively. That got them back in the game.
The good news is we found a way to win."

Sam scored nine straight points early in the second half,
reducing a 10-point deficit to 45-41 on two free throws with 13:44
to play.

Charlotte later pulled within two, 51-49, on a three-point play
by Tangela Smith with 9:06 left. Tully Bevilaqua responded with a
3-pointer for Indiana, and the Sting never drew closer than three
points again.

Charlotte didn't get a field goal in the final 4:46 as Indiana
closed the game with 8-2 run.

The 10 offensive boards by Catchings was a league high this
season as was the 21 total by the team.

"Certain teams don't box out as well as others," said
Williams, who has announced she plans to retire at the end of the
season. "Charlotte has been not been known to box out well. Tamika
did a great job on the boards."

"I've only got three more games left in the regular season and
then I'm done," said the 34-year-old, who has scored in double
figures in her last three games. "I'm just trying to give
everything I got."

The win allowed Indiana (19-12) to extend its franchise records
for victories in a season and at home (13). Charlotte (4-27) has
lost 18 consecutive road games. Its last road win was Sept. 8 at
Minnesota last season.

Indiana also maintained its one-game advantage over the New York
Liberty in the battle for second place in the WNBA's Eastern
Conference.

The Fever opened a 10-point lead in the game's first seven
minutes but saw the Sting pull to 18-14 before going up 33-22 with
six consecutive points late in the half.

Catchings had 12 points and eight rebounds in the first half,
which ended with the Fever holding a 35-26 advantage.
